<p><b>Mazda Motor Corporation</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji" lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">マツダ株式会社</span><span class="t_nihongo_comma" style="display:none">,</span> <i>Matsuda Kabushiki-gaisha</i><sup class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><a href="/wiki/Help:Installing_Japanese_character_sets" title="Help:Installing Japanese character sets"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup>)</span>, commonly referred to just as <b>Mazda</b>, is a Japanese <a href="/wiki/Multinational_corporation" title="Multinational corporation">multinational</a> <a href="/wiki/Automaker" class="mw-redirect" title="Automaker">automaker</a> based in <a href="/wiki/Fuch%C5%AB,_Hiroshima_(town)" title="Fuchū, Hiroshima (town)">Fuchū</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aki_District,_Hiroshima" title="Aki District, Hiroshima">Aki District</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hiroshima_Prefecture" title="Hiroshima Prefecture">Hiroshima Prefecture</a>, Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2007, Mazda produced almost 1.3&#160;million vehicles for global sales, the majority of which (nearly 1 million) were produced in the company's Japanese plants, with the remainder coming from a variety of other plants worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> In 2011, Mazda was the fifteenth biggest automaker by production worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Name">Name</span></h2>
<p>Mazda's company website states that its name is derived from <a href="/wiki/Ahura_Mazda" title="Ahura Mazda">Ahura Mazda</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Avestan" title="Avestan">Avestan</a> word for God (<a href="/wiki/Modern_Persian" class="mw-redirect" title="Modern Persian">Modern Persian</a>: اهورا مزدا-<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: असुर मेधा [Asura-Medhā]), which is also the name of God to <a href="/wiki/Zoroastrianism" title="Zoroastrianism">Zoroastrians</a>. Specifically, the company states that</p>
<blockquote>
<p><i>The name was also associated with Ahura Mazda (God of Light), with the hope that it would brighten the image of these compact vehicles.</i></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The company website further notes that the name also derives from the name of the company's founder, <a href="/wiki/Jujiro_Matsuda" title="Jujiro Matsuda">Jujiro Matsuda</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<p>Mazda began as the Toyo Cork Kogyo Co., Ltd, founded in <a href="/wiki/Hiroshima" title="Hiroshima">Hiroshima</a>, Japan, in 1920. Toyo Cork Kogyo renamed itself to Toyo Kogyo Co., Ltd. in 1927. In the late 1920s the company had to be saved from bankruptcy by Hiroshima Saving Bank and other business leaders in Hiroshima.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1931 Toyo Kogyo moved from manufacturing machine tools to vehicles with the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Mazdago" title="Mazda Mazdago">Mazda-Go</a> <a href="/wiki/Autorickshaw" class="mw-redirect" title="Autorickshaw">autorickshaw</a>. Toyo Kogyo produced weapons for the Japanese military throughout the Second World War, most notably the series 30 through 35 <a href="/wiki/Type_99_rifle" title="Type 99 rifle">Type 99 rifle</a>. The company formally adopted the Mazda name in 1984, though every automobile sold from the beginning bore that name. The <a href="/wiki/Mazda_R360" title="Mazda R360">Mazda R360</a> was introduced in 1960, followed by the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Carol" title="Mazda Carol">Mazda Carol</a> in 1962.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg/220px-Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg/330px-Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg/440px-Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2272" data-file-height="1704" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mazda_cosmo_sport.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Mazda_Cosmo" title="Mazda Cosmo">Mazda Cosmo</a> Sport</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Beginning in the 1960s, Mazda was inspired by the <a href="/wiki/NSU_Ro_80" title="NSU Ro 80">NSU Ro 80</a>, and decided to put a major engineering effort into development of the <a href="/wiki/Wankel_engine" title="Wankel engine">Wankel rotary engine</a> as a way of differentiating itself from other Japanese auto companies. The company formed a business relationship with German company <a href="/wiki/NSU_Motorenwerke_AG" class="mw-redirect" title="NSU Motorenwerke AG">NSU</a>, and began with the limited-production <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Cosmo" title="Mazda Cosmo">Cosmo Sport</a> of 1967 and continuing to the present day with the <a href="/wiki/Pro_Mazda_Championship" title="Pro Mazda Championship">Pro Mazda Championship</a>, Mazda has become the sole manufacturer of Wankel-type engines for the automotive market mainly by way of attrition (NSU and <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn" title="Citroën">Citroën</a> both gave up on the design during the 1970s, and prototype Corvette efforts by <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" title="General Motors">General Motors</a> never made it to production.)</p>
<p>This effort to bring attention to itself apparently helped, as Mazda rapidly began to export its vehicles. Both <a href="/wiki/Reciprocating_engine" title="Reciprocating engine">piston-powered</a> and rotary-powered models made their way around the world. The rotary models quickly became popular for their combination of good power and light weight when compared to piston-engined competitors that required heavier <a href="/wiki/V6_engine" title="V6 engine">V6</a> or <a href="/wiki/V8_engine" title="V8 engine">V8</a> engines to produce the same power. The <a href="/wiki/Mazda_R100" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda R100">R100</a> and the RX series (<a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-2" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-2">RX-2</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-3" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-3">RX-3</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-4" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-4">RX-4</a>) led the company's export efforts.</p>
<p>During 1968, Mazda started formal operations in Canada (MazdaCanada) although Mazdas were seen in Canada as early as 1959. In 1970, Mazda formally entered the American market (<a href="/wiki/Mazda_North_American_Operations" title="Mazda North American Operations">Mazda North American Operations</a>) and was very successful there, going so far as to create the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Rotary_Pickup" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda Rotary Pickup">Mazda Rotary Pickup</a> (based on the conventional piston-powered <a href="/wiki/Mazda_B-Series_(International)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda B-Series (International)">B-Series</a> model) solely for North American buyers. To this day, Mazda remains the only automaker to have produced a Wankel-powered pickup truck. Additionally, it is also the only marque to have ever offered a rotary-powered bus (the Mazda Parkway, offered only in Japan) or station wagon (within the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-3" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-3">RX-3</a> and RX-4 lines for certain markets). After nine years of development, Mazda finally launched its new model in the U.S. in 1970.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></p>
<p>Mazda's rotary success continued until the onset of the <a href="/wiki/1973_oil_crisis" title="1973 oil crisis">1973 oil crisis</a>. As American buyers (as well as those in other nations) quickly turned to vehicles with better fuel efficiency, the relatively thirsty rotary-powered models began to fall out of favor. Combined with being the least-efficient automaker in Japan (in terms of productivity), inability to adjust to excess inventory and over-reliance on the U.S. market, the company suffered a huge loss in 1975.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> An already heavily indebted Toyo Kogyo was on the verge of bankruptcy and was only saved through the intervention of Sumitomo keiretsu group, namely <a href="/wiki/Sumitomo_Mitsui_Banking_Corporation" title="Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation">Sumitomo Bank</a>, and the companies subcontractors and distributors.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> Fortunately, the company had not totally turned its back on piston engines, as it continued to produce a variety of four-cylinder models throughout the 1970s. The smaller <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Familia" title="Mazda Familia">Familia</a> line in particular became very important to Mazda's worldwide sales after 1973, as did the somewhat larger <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Capella" title="Mazda Capella">Capella</a> series.</p>

<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg/220px-Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg/330px-Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg/440px-Mazda-rx7-1st-generation01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2272" data-file-height="1704" /></a>

Mazda RX-7 (first generation)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Mazda refocused its efforts and made the rotary engine a choice for the sporting motorist rather than a mainstream powerplant. Starting with the lightweight <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-7" title="Mazda RX-7">RX-7</a> in 1978 and continuing with the modern <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-8" title="Mazda RX-8">RX-8</a>, Mazda has continued its dedication to this unique powerplant. This switch in focus also resulted in the development of another lightweight sports car, the piston-powered <a href="/wiki/Mazda_MX-5" title="Mazda MX-5">Mazda Roadster</a> (perhaps better known by its worldwide names as the MX-5 or <a href="/wiki/Miata" class="mw-redirect" title="Miata">Miata</a>), inspired by the concept '<a href="/wiki/Jinba_ittai" title="Jinba ittai">jinba ittai</a>'. Introduced in 1989 to worldwide acclaim, the Roadster has been widely credited with reviving the concept of the small sports car after its decline in the late 1970s.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Partnership_with_Ford_Motor_Company">Partnership with Ford Motor Company</span></h3>
<p>From 1974 to 2015, Mazda had a partnership with the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a>, which acquired a 7% stake in 1979, and by 1996 owned 33.3% of Mazda. Under the administration of <a href="/wiki/Alan_Mulally" title="Alan Mulally">Alan Mulally</a>, Ford gradually divested its stake in Mazda from 2008 to 2015, with Ford currently holding 2.1% of Mazda stock in 2014<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> and severing most production as well as development ties.</p>
<p>This partnership with <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a> began due to Mazda's financial difficulties during the 1960s. Starting in 1979 with a 7-percent financial stake, Ford expanded an existing partnership with Mazda resulting in various joint projects. The cooperation had begun in 1971 when the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_B-Series" title="Mazda B-Series">Mazda B-Series</a> spawned a Ford Courier variant for North America, a version which was later offered in other markets as well. Mazda's <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Bongo" title="Mazda Bongo">Bongo</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Titan" title="Mazda Titan">Titan</a> cab-over trucks were sold with Ford badging in mainly Asia and the Pacific region beginning in 1976.<sup id="cite_ref-annual80_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-annual80-14">[14]</a></sup> These included large and small efforts in all areas of the automotive landscape — most notably in the realm of pickup trucks and smaller cars. Mazda began supplying manual transaxles to Ford in the spring of 1980.<sup id="cite_ref-annual80_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-annual80-14">[14]</a></sup> Mazda's Familia platform was used for Ford models like the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Laser" title="Ford Laser">Laser</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ford_Escort_(North_America)" title="Ford Escort (North America)">Escort</a> beginning in 1980, while the Capella architecture found its way into Ford's <a href="/wiki/Ford_Telstar" title="Ford Telstar">Telstar</a> sedan and <a href="/wiki/Ford_Probe" title="Ford Probe">Probe</a> sports models. During the 1980s, Ford gained another 20-percent financial stake, and in 2002 Ford gained an extra 5-percent financial stake. Particularly in the Asia-Pacific markets, Ford-badged Mazda products replaced much of their own lineup. The Ford Festiva, Laser, and Telstar were also sold in Japan alongside their Mazda-badged brethren.</p>
<p>The Probe was built in a new Mazda company plant in <a href="/wiki/Flat_Rock,_Michigan" title="Flat Rock, Michigan">Flat Rock, Michigan</a> along with the mainstream 626 sedan (the North American version of the Capella) and a companion <a href="/wiki/Mazda_MX-6" title="Mazda MX-6">Mazda MX-6</a> sports coupe. Ford also lent Mazda some of its capacity when needed: the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_121" title="Mazda 121">Mazda 121</a> sold in Europe and South Africa was, for a time, a variant of the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Fiesta" title="Ford Fiesta">Ford Fiesta</a> built in plants in Europe and South Africa. Mazda also made an effort in the past to sell some of Ford's cars in Japan, mainly through its Autorama dealer group.</p>
<p>Mazda also helped Ford develop the 1991 <a href="/wiki/Ford_Explorer" title="Ford Explorer">Explorer</a>, which Mazda sold as the 2-door only <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Navajo" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda Navajo">Mazda Navajo</a> from 1991 through 1994. Ironically, Mazda's version was unsuccessful, while the Ford (available from the start as a 4-door or 2-door model) instantly became the best selling sport-utility vehicle in the United States and kept that title for over a decade. Mazda has used Ford's <a href="/wiki/Ford_Ranger" title="Ford Ranger">Ranger</a> pickup as the basis for its North American–market <a href="/wiki/Mazda_B-Series_(North_America)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda B-Series (North America)">B-Series</a> trucks, starting in 1994 and continuing through 2010, when Mazda discontinued importing its B-Series trucks to North America, due to costs associated with the <a href="/wiki/Chicken_tax" title="Chicken tax">chicken tax</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup></p>

<p>Following its long-held fascination with alternative engine technology, Mazda introduced the first <a href="/wiki/Miller_cycle" title="Miller cycle">Miller cycle</a> engine for automotive use in the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Millenia" title="Mazda Millenia">Millenia</a> luxury sedan of 1995. Though the Millenia (and its Miller-type V6 engine) were discontinued in 2002, the company has recently introduced a much smaller Miller-cycle four-cylinder engine for use in its <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Demio" title="Mazda Demio">Demio</a> starting in 2008. As with its leadership in <a href="/wiki/Wankel_engine" title="Wankel engine">Wankel technology</a>, Mazda remains (so far) the only automaker to have used a Miller-cycle engine in the automotive realm.</p>

<p>Further financial difficulties at Mazda during the 1990s (partly caused by losses related to the <a href="/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis" title="1997 Asian financial crisis">1997 Asian financial crisis</a>) caused Ford to increase its stake to a 33.4-percent <a href="/wiki/Controlling_interest" title="Controlling interest">controlling interest</a> in May 1996. In June 1996, Henry Wallace was appointed President, and he set about restructuring Mazda and setting it on a new strategic direction. He laid out a new direction for the brand including the design of the present Mazda marque; he laid out a new product plan to achieve synergies with Ford, and he launched Mazda's digital innovation program to speed up the development of new products. At the same time, he started taking control of overseas distributors, rationalized dealerships and manufacturing facilities, and driving much needed efficiencies and cost reductions in Mazda's operations. Much of his early work put Mazda back into profitability and laid the foundations for future success. Wallace was succeeded by James Miller in November 1997, followed in December 1999 by Ford executive <a href="/wiki/Mark_Fields_(businessman)" title="Mark Fields (businessman)">Mark Fields</a>, who has been credited with expanding Mazda's new product lineup and leading the turnaround during the early 2000s. Ford's increased influence during the 1990s allowed Mazda to claim another distinction in history, having maintained the first foreign-born head of a Japanese car company, Henry Wallace.</p>

<p>Amid the world financial crisis in the fall of 2008, reports emerged that Ford was contemplating a sale of its stake in Mazda as a way of <a href="/wiki/Process_optimization" title="Process optimization">streamlining</a> its <a href="/wiki/Asset" title="Asset">asset</a> base.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/BusinessWeek" class="mw-redirect" title="BusinessWeek">BusinessWeek</a></i> explained the alliance between Ford and Mazda has been a very successful one, with Mazda saving perhaps $90&#160;million a year in development costs and Ford "several times" that, and that a sale of its stake in Mazda would be a desperate measure.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> On November 18, 2008, Ford announced that it would sell a 20% stake in Mazda, reducing its stake to 13.4% thus surrendering control of the company, which it held since 1996.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> The following day, Mazda announced that, as part of the deal, it was buying back 6.8% of its shares from Ford for about US$185 million while the rest would be acquired by business partners of the company.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> It was also reported that Hisakazu Imaki would be stepping down as chief executive, to be replaced by Takashi Yamanouchi.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> On November 18, 2010, Ford reduced its stake further to 3%, citing the reduction of ownership would allow greater flexibility to pursue growth in emerging markets, and <a href="/wiki/Sumitomo_Mitsui_Financial_Group" title="Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group">Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group</a> was believed to become its largest shareholder. Ford and Mazda remained strategic partners through joint ventures and exchanges of technological information.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup></p>

<p>On September 30, 2015, when Ford's shares had sunk to a little over 2% due to <a href="/wiki/Stock_dilution" title="Stock dilution">stock dilution</a>, Ford sold its remaining shares in Mazda.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Post-partnership_with_Ford">Post-partnership with Ford</span></h3>
<p>In 2011, Mazda raised more than 150 billion yen (US$1.9 billion) in a record share sale to replenish capital, as it suffered its biggest annual loss in 11 years. Part of the proceeds were used to build an auto plant in <a href="/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> The Mexican plant was built jointly by the company and <a href="/wiki/Sumitomo_Corporation" title="Sumitomo Corporation">Sumitomo Corporation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup></p>
<p>In May 2015, the company signed an agreement with <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a> to form a "long-term partnership", that would, among others, see Mazda supply Toyota with fuel-efficient SkyActiv gasoline and diesel engine technology, in exchange for hydrogen fuel cell systems.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup></p>

<p>Mazda previously used a number of different <a href="/wiki/Marque" class="mw-redirect" title="Marque">marques</a> in the Japanese (and occasionally Australian) market, including <a href="/wiki/Autozam" title="Autozam">Autozam</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eunos_cars" class="mw-redirect" title="Eunos cars">Eunos</a>, and <a href="/wiki/%C6%90%CC%83fini" title="Ɛ̃fini">ɛ̃fini</a>, which have since been phased out. The motivation was brought on by market competition from other Japanese automakers efforts in offering vehicles at multiple Japanese dealership networks offered by <a href="/wiki/Toyota#Japan" title="Toyota">Toyota</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Motor_Company#Japan" class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Motor Company">Nissan</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Honda#Japan" title="Honda">Honda</a>. Mazda's implementation of brand diversification reflected a Japanese engineering philosophy, called <a href="/wiki/Kansei_engineering" title="Kansei engineering">Kansei engineering</a>, which was used as an advertising slogan in North America. This selective marketing experiment was ended in the mid-1990s due to economic conditions, largely attributed to the collapse of the <a href="/wiki/Japanese_asset_price_bubble" title="Japanese asset price bubble">Japanese asset price bubble</a> in 1991.</p>
<p>This diversification stressed the product development groups at Mazda past its limits. Instead of having a half-dozen variations on any given <a href="/wiki/List_of_Mazda_platforms" title="List of Mazda platforms">platform</a>, developers were asked to work on dozens of different models and consumers were confused as well by the explosion of similar new models. One of the oddest sub-marques was <a href="/wiki/M2_(Mazda)" title="M2 (Mazda)">M2</a>, used on three rare variants of the Eunos Roadster (the M2-1001, M2-1002 and M2-1028) and one of the Autozam AZ-1 (M2-1015). M2 even had its own avant-garde company headquarters, but was shut down after a very short period of operation.</p>
<p>Today, the former marques no longer exist in Japan as sales channels. The <a href="/wiki/Autozam_Carol" class="mw-redirect" title="Autozam Carol">Carol</a> was sold at the <a href="/wiki/Autozam" title="Autozam">Autozam</a> store (which specialized in small cars), but it now sold with the Mazda marque, not as the <i>Autozam Carol</i> as it once was.</p>
<p>In early 1992 Mazda planned to release a luxury marque, <a href="/wiki/Amati_Cars" title="Amati Cars">Amati</a>, to challenge <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acura</a>, <a href="/wiki/Infiniti" title="Infiniti">Infiniti</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lexus" title="Lexus">Lexus</a> in North America, which was to begin selling in late 1993. The initial Amati range would have included the Amati 500 (which became the Eunos 800 in Japan and Australia, <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Millenia" title="Mazda Millenia">Mazda Millenia</a> in the U.S., and Mazda Xedos 9 in Europe), a rebadged version of the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Cosmo#Series_JC_.281990.E2.80.931996.29" title="Mazda Cosmo">Mazda Cosmo</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Amati_1000" class="mw-redirect" title="Amati 1000">Amati 1000</a> (a rear-wheel drive W12 successor to the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Luce" title="Mazda Luce">Mazda Luce</a>). The Amati marque was eventually scrapped before any cars hit the market. It is perhaps just a curiosity, but "Amati" happens to be an anagram of "Miata"</p>
<p>In Europe, the <a href="/wiki/Xedos" class="mw-redirect" title="Xedos">Xedos</a> name was also associated with the Mazda <a href="/wiki/Xedos_6" class="mw-redirect" title="Xedos 6">Xedos 6</a>, the two models were in production from 1992 until 1997. The Xedos line was marketed under the Mazda marque, and used the Mazda badge from the corresponding years.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Environmental_efforts">Environmental efforts</span></h2>
<p>Mazda has conducted research in hydrogen-powered vehicles for several decades. Mazda has developed a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrid</a> version of its <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Premacy" title="Mazda Premacy">Premacy</a> compact minivan using a version of its signature rotary engine that can run on hydrogen or gasoline. Despite plans to release it in 2008,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-autocar.co.uk_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autocar.co.uk-29">[29]</a></sup> as of 2010 the vehicle is in limited trials.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2010 <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a> and Mazda announced a supply agreement for the hybrid technology used in Toyota's <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Prius" title="Toyota Prius">Prius</a> model.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Bio-Car">Bio-Car</span></h3>
<p>Mazda is finding a host of alternative uses for a variety of materials and substances – ranging from plastic to milk – in its vehicles, as it aims to become more environmentally-friendly. Mazda introduced some of these innovations – bioplastic internal consoles and bio-fabric seats – in its <a href="/wiki/Mazda5" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda5">Mazda5</a> model at <a href="/wiki/EcoInnovasia" class="mw-redirect" title="EcoInnovasia">EcoInnovasia</a> 2008, at the <a href="/wiki/Queen_Sirikit_National_Convention_Center" title="Queen Sirikit National Convention Center">Queen Sirikit National Convention Center</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bangkok" title="Bangkok">Bangkok</a>. Up to 30% of the interior parts in the Mazda5 are made of non-biomaterial components, e.g. Poti (gobar of cows).<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="SkyActiv_Technology">SkyActiv Technology</span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/SkyActiv" title="SkyActiv">SkyActiv</a> technology is an umbrella name for a range of technologies used in certain new Mazda vehicles. These vehicles include the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Demio" title="Mazda Demio">Mazda2/Demio</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mazda6" title="Mazda6">Mazda6/Atenza</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mazda_CX-5" title="Mazda CX-5">CX-5</a> and 2014 Mazda 3. Together these technologies increase fuel economy to a level similar to a hybrid drivetrain. Engine output is increased and emission levels are reduced. These technologies include high compression ratio gasoline engines (13.0 to 1), reduced compression diesel engines (14.0 to 1) with new 2-stage <a href="/wiki/Turbocharger" title="Turbocharger">turbocharger</a> design, highly efficient automatic transmissions, lighter weight manual transmissions, lightweight body designs and <a href="/wiki/Electric_power_steering#Electric_systems" class="mw-redirect" title="Electric power steering">electric power steering</a>. It is also possible to combine these technologies with a hybrid drivetrain for even greater fuel economy.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Mazdaspeed" title="Mazdaspeed">Mazdaspeed</a></div>
<p>In the racing world, Mazda has had substantial success with both its signature Wankel-engine cars (in two-rotor, three-rotor, and four-rotor forms) as well as its piston-engine models. Mazda vehicles and engines compete in a wide variety of disciplines and series around the world. More Mazdas are raced every week than any other car brand<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> (a large part of this statement speaks to the success of the MX-5/Miata and its widespread embrace by grassroots motorsports). As of 2014, Mazda remains the only Japanese automaker to win the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="24 Hours of Le Mans">24 Hours of Le Mans</a> overall.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="International_competition">International competition</span></h3>
<p>Mazda's competition debut was on October 20, 1968 when two <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Cosmo#Racing" title="Mazda Cosmo">Mazda Cosmo Sport 110S</a> coupes entered the 84 hour <a href="/w/index.php?title=Marathon_de_la_Route&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Marathon de la Route (page does not exist)">Marathon de la Route</a> ultra-endurance race at the <a href="/wiki/N%C3%BCrburgring" title="Nürburgring">Nürburgring</a>, one finishing in fourth place and the other breaking an axle after 81 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-a_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-a-33">[33]</a></sup> The next year, Mazda raced <a href="/wiki/Mazda_R100#Racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda R100">Mazda Familia R100 M10A</a> coupes. After winning the <a href="/wiki/Singapore_Grand_Prix" title="Singapore Grand Prix">Singapore Grand Prix</a> in April 1969 and coming in fifth and sixth in the <a href="/wiki/Spa_24_Hours" title="Spa 24 Hours">Spa 24 Hours</a> (beaten only by <a href="/wiki/Porsche_911" title="Porsche 911">Porsche 911s</a>), on October 19, 1969, Mazda again entered the 84 hour Nürburgring race with four Familias. Only one of these finished, taking fifth place.</p>
<p>The first racing victory by a Wankel-engined car in the United States was in 1973, when <a href="/wiki/Pat_Bedard" class="mw-redirect" title="Pat Bedard">Pat Bedard</a> won an <a href="/wiki/International_Motor_Sports_Association#IMSA_RS" title="International Motor Sports Association">IMSA RS</a> race at <a href="/wiki/Lime_Rock_Park" title="Lime Rock Park">Lime Rock Park</a> in a <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-2" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-2">Mazda RX-2</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-a_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-a-33">[33]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1976, Ray Walle, owner of Z&amp;W Mazda, drove a Cosmo (<a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-5" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-5">Mazda RX-5</a>) from the dealership in Princeton, New Jersey, to Daytona, won the Touring Class Under 2.5 Liters at the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Daytona" title="24 Hours of Daytona">24 Hours of Daytona</a>, and drove the car back to New Jersey. The Cosmo placed 18th overall in a field of 72. The only modifications were racing brake pads, exhaust, and safety equipment.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup></p>
<p>After substantial successes by the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-2" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-2">Mazda RX-2</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-3" class="mw-redirect" title="Mazda RX-3">Mazda RX-3</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-7" title="Mazda RX-7">Mazda RX-7</a> has won more <a href="/wiki/International_Motor_Sports_Association" title="International Motor Sports Association">IMSA</a> races in its class than any other model of automobile, with its hundredth victory on September 2, 1990. Following that, the RX-7 won its class in the IMSA <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Daytona" title="24 Hours of Daytona">24 Hours of Daytona</a> race ten years in a row, starting in 1982. The RX-7 won the IMSA Grand Touring Under Two Liter (GTU) championship each year from 1980 through 1987, inclusive.</p>

The <a href="/wiki/Mazda_787B" title="Mazda 787B">Mazda 787B</a>, winner of the 1991 <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="24 Hours of Le Mans">24 Hours of Le Mans</a> race</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1991, a four-rotor <a href="/wiki/Mazda_787B" title="Mazda 787B">Mazda 787B</a> (2622 cc actual, rated by <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">FIA</a> formula at 4708 cc) won the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="24 Hours of Le Mans">24 Hours of Le Mans</a> auto race outright. The 787B's triumph remains unparalleled, as it remains the only non-piston-engined car ever to win at Le Mans, and Mazda is still the only Japanese marque to have won overall at Le Mans – ironically<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style_(words_to_watch)#Editorializing" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style (words to watch)"><span title="A statement that draws an independent conclusion. (April 2013)">editorializing</span></a></i>]</sup> after <a href="/wiki/Nissan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a> had closed down its <a href="/wiki/World_Sportscar_Championship" title="World Sportscar Championship">World Sportscar Championship</a> programme and <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a> had opted to take a sabbatical for most of 1991 in order to develop its 3.5-litre <a href="/wiki/Toyota_TS010" title="Toyota TS010">TS010</a>. This led to a ban on rotary engines in the Le Mans race starting in 1992, which has since been rescinded. After the 1991 race, the winning engine was publicly dismantled for internal examination, which demonstrated that despite 24 hours of extremely hard use it had accumulated very little wear.</p>
<p>The Le Mans win in 1991 followed a decade of class wins from other Mazda prototypes, including the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_757" title="Mazda 757">757</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mazda_767" title="Mazda 767">767</a>. The Sigma MC74 powered by a Mazda 12A engine was the first engine and team from outside Western Europe or the United States to finish the entire 24 hours of the Le Mans race, in 1974. Mazda is also the most reliable finisher at Le Mans (with the exception of <a href="/wiki/Honda" title="Honda">Honda</a>, which has entered only three cars in only one year), with 67% of entries finishing. Mazda will return to prototype racing in 2005 with the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Courage_Comp%C3%A9tition" title="Courage Compétition">Courage</a> C65 LMP2 car at the <a href="/wiki/American_Le_Mans_Series" title="American Le Mans Series">American Le Mans Series</a> race at <a href="/wiki/Road_Atlanta" title="Road Atlanta">Road Atlanta</a>. This prototype racer uses the Renesis Wankel from the RX-8.</p>
<p>Mazdas have also enjoyed substantial success in <a href="/wiki/Land_speed_record" title="Land speed record">World Land Speed</a> competition, <a href="/wiki/SCCA" class="mw-redirect" title="SCCA">SCCA</a> competition, <a href="/wiki/Drag_racing" title="Drag racing">drag racing</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rally_racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Rally racing">pro rally</a> competition (the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Familia" title="Mazda Familia">Familia</a> appeared in the <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">WRC</a> several times during the late '80s and early '90s), the <a href="/wiki/One_Lap_of_America" title="One Lap of America">One Lap of America</a> race (winning SUV &amp; truck in a MazdaSpeed5), and other venues. Wankel engines have been banned for some time from international <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> racing,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2010)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> as well as from United States <a href="/wiki/Midget_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Midget car">midget racing</a>, after <a href="/w/index.php?title=Gene_Angelillo&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Gene Angelillo (page does not exist)">Gene Angelillo</a> won the <a href="/w/index.php?title=North_East_Midget_Racing_Association&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="North East Midget Racing Association (page does not exist)">North East Midget Racing Association</a> championship in 1985 with a car powered by a 13B engine, and again in 1986 in a car powered by a 12A engine.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Spec_series">Spec series</span></h3>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Atlantic_Championship" title="Atlantic Championship">Cooper Tires Atlantic Championship powered by Mazda</a> is a North American <a href="/wiki/Open_wheel" class="mw-redirect" title="Open wheel">open wheel</a> racing series. It is the top level of the MAZDASPEED ladder, a driver development program which rewards season winners of one level with automatic rides at the next level. Since 2006, the Atlantic Championship has been run exclusively with <a href="/wiki/Swift_Engineering" title="Swift Engineering">Swift</a> 016.a chassis powered by Mazda-<a href="/wiki/Cosworth" title="Cosworth">Cosworth</a> MZR 2300 cc (2.3L) <a href="/wiki/DOHC" class="mw-redirect" title="DOHC">DOHC</a> <a href="/wiki/Inline-4" class="mw-redirect" title="Inline-4">inline-4</a> engines producing 300&#160;bhp (224&#160;kW). The cars are capable of speeds in excess of 175&#160;mph (282&#160;km/h).<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup></p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Formula_Mazda_Racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Formula Mazda Racing">Formula Mazda Racing</a> features open wheel race cars with Mazda engines, adaptable to both oval tracks and road courses, on several levels of competition. Since 1991, the professionally organized <a href="/wiki/Star_Mazda_Series" class="mw-redirect" title="Star Mazda Series">Star Mazda Series</a> has been the most popular format for sponsors, spectators, and upward bound drivers. It is the second-highest level on the aforementioned MAZDASPEED driver development ladder. Engines for the Star Mazda series are all built by one engine builder, certified to produce the prescribed power, and sealed to discourage tampering. They are in a relatively mild state of racing tune, so that they are extremely reliable and can go years between motor rebuilds.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Spec_Miata" title="Spec Miata">Spec Miata</a> has become one of the most popular and most affordable road racing classes in North America. The Spec Miata (SM) class is intended to provide the opportunity to compete in low cost, production-based cars with limited modifications, suitable for racing competition. The rules are intentionally designed to be more open than the Showroom Stock class but more restricted than the Improved Touring class.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Spec_RX7" class="mw-redirect" title="Spec RX7">Spec RX7</a> is also a popular club racing class primarily due to the availability of first generation RX7 cars and the low startup cost.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>

<p>Mazda is a major sponsor to several professional sports teams, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>Hometown teams:
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sanfrecce_Hiroshima" title="Sanfrecce Hiroshima">Sanfrecce Hiroshima</a> (<a href="/wiki/J._League" class="mw-redirect" title="J. League">J. League</a>): Originally known as Toyo Kogyo Soccer Club and founded in 1938, it was owned directly by Mazda until 1992 when Mazda reduced its share to professionalize the club for the new J. League.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hiroshima_Toyo_Carp" title="Hiroshima Toyo Carp">Hiroshima Toyo Carp</a> (<a href="/wiki/Nippon_Professional_Baseball" title="Nippon Professional Baseball">Nippon Professional Baseball</a>): The "Toyo" part of the team's name is in honor of Mazda's part-ownership of the team since 1968 (when Mazda was still known as Toyo Kogyo). The Matsuda family, descended from the founder of Mazda, holds the majority share in team ownership.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Teams abroad:
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/North_Melbourne_Football_Club" title="North Melbourne Football Club">North Melbourne Football Club</a> (<a href="/wiki/Australian_Football_League" title="Australian Football League">Australian Football League</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/ACF_Fiorentina" title="ACF Fiorentina">ACF Fiorentina</a> (Italian football league – <a href="/wiki/Serie_A" title="Serie A">Serie A</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nakhon_Ratchasima_F.C." title="Nakhon Ratchasima F.C.">Nakhon Ratchasima</a> (Thai football league – <a href="/wiki/Thai_Division_1_League" class="mw-redirect" title="Thai Division 1 League">Yamaha League 1</a>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The company also sponsors various <a href="/wiki/Marathon" title="Marathon">marathon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Relay_race" title="Relay race">relay race</a> events in Japan, such as the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hiroshima_International_Peace_Marathon&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hiroshima International Peace Marathon (page does not exist)">Hiroshima International Peace Marathon</a> and the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hiroshima_Prefectural_Ekiden_Race&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hiroshima Prefectural Ekiden Race (page does not exist)">Hiroshima Prefectural Ekiden Race</a>, along with numerous other sporting and charity endeavors in <a href="/wiki/Hiroshima" title="Hiroshima">Hiroshima</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hofu" class="mw-redirect" title="Hofu">Hofu</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> Mazda was also the league sponsor for the now-defunct <a href="/wiki/Australian_Rugby_Championship" title="Australian Rugby Championship">Australian Rugby Championship</a>.</p>
<p>Mazda also maintains sponsorship of the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Raceway_Laguna_Seca" title="Mazda Raceway Laguna Seca">Laguna Seca</a> racing course in California, going so far as to use it for its own automotive testing purposes as well as the numerous racing events (including several Mazda-specific series) that it hosts – as well as for the 2003 launch of the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_RX-8" title="Mazda RX-8">Mazda RX-8</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup></p>
<p>Mazda also sponsors the <a href="/wiki/Western_New_York_Flash" title="Western New York Flash">Western New York Flash</a>, a professional women's soccer team that plays in the <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_Professional_Soccer" title="Women's Professional Soccer">WPA</a> and has some of the best players in the world, including world player of the year.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">Marketing</span></h2>
<p>Mazda's past advertising slogans included: "The more you look, the more you like" (1970s to early 1980s); "Experience Mazda" (mid-1980s); "An intense commitment to your total satisfaction, that's The Mazda Way" (late 1980s); "It Just Feels Right" along with advertising describing Mazda's use of <a href="/wiki/Kansei_engineering" title="Kansei engineering">Kansei engineering</a> (1990–1995); "Passion for the road" (1996); "Get in. Be moved." (1997–1999)</p>
<p>Since 2000, Mazda has used the phrase "Zoom-Zoom" to describe what it calls the "emotion of motion" that it claims is inherent in its cars.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup> Extremely successful and long-lasting (when compared to other automotive marketing taglines), the Zoom-Zoom campaign has now spread around the world from its initial use in North America.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-3">[3]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Zoom-Zoom campaign has been accompanied by the "<a href="/wiki/Zoom-Zoom-Zoom" title="Zoom-Zoom-Zoom">Zoom-Zoom-Zoom</a>" song in many television and radio advertisements. The original version, performed by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Jibril_Serapis_Bey&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Jibril Serapis Bey (page does not exist)">Jibril Serapis Bey</a> (used in commercials in Europe, Japan and South Africa), was recorded long before it became the official song for Mazda as part of a soundtrack to the movie <i><a href="/wiki/Only_the_Strong_(film)" title="Only the Strong (film)">Only The Strong</a></i> (released in 1993). The Serapis Bey version is a cover of a traditional <a href="/wiki/Capoeira_music" title="Capoeira music">Capoeira song</a>, called "Capoeira Mata Um". In 2010, its current slogan is "Zoom Zoom Forever". The longer slogan (Used in TV ads) is "Zoom Zoom, Today, Tomorrow, Forever".</p>
<p>Early ads in the Zoom-Zoom campaign also featured a young boy (Micah Kanters) whispering the "Zoom-Zoom" tagline.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2011, Mazda has still used the Zoom-Zoom tagline in another campaign called "What Do You Drive?". The punchline for this is "At Mazda, we believe because if it's not worth driving, it's not worth building. We build Mazdas. What do you drive?".</p>
<p>In 2015, Mazda had launched a new campaign under a new tagline, "Driving Matters", conceding with the release of the redesigned MX-5.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> This campaign was meant to solidify Mazda's "Zoom Zoom" slogan. A 60-second long advertisement titled "A Driver's Life", conceded with the new tagline on the following week.</p>
